      "side": 1,
      "message": "“Dangerous,” I don’t know about that. I did find a way to get -[NSString UTF8String] to return nullptr for a “valid” NSString. Hint: the NSString isn’t really valid, but it’s not nil, either.\n\n  unichar c \u003d 0xd800;  // Anything in range [0xd800, 0xc000)\n  NSString* s \u003d [NSString stringWithCharacters:\u0026c length:1];\n  // Result:\n  // s !\u003d nil\n  // [s UTF8String] \u003d\u003d nullptr\n\nu+d800…u+dfff are UTF-16 surrogates, and by placing just a single surrogate, the UTF-16 sequence is invalid. But you still get a live NSString from it, and one for which -UTF8String fails.\n\nI couldn’t get this to happen when initializing from invalid UTF-8 input. Here’s a UTF-8 continuation byte not preceded by a lead byte, and a lead byte not followed by a continuation byte:\n\n  NSString* s1 \u003d [NSString stringWithUTF8String:\"\\x80\"];\n  NSString* s2 \u003d [NSString stringWithUTF8String:\"\\xc0\\x01\"];\n  // Result:\n  // s1 \u003d\u003d s2 \u003d\u003d nil\n\nMeanwhile, SysNSStringToUTF8 does paper over the problem by returning an empty std::string for bad Unicode input.\n\nWe have a couple uses of -UTF8String elsewhere in Crashpad (a couple, even, in non-test code). We should evaluate whether they’re safe.",
      "parentUuid": "6753e8a3_49c92ede",
      "revId": "b0041a44ecc69737a0c779ff94315d8147fd785c",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
